<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0015 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0058EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-TennesseeAt-A-Glance     03-08 0206</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Tennessee At-A-Glance,220</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Tennessee to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 70   Super delegates: 7   Total: 77   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, March 26 and Saturday, April 9   All of Tennessee's 70 pledged delegates to the DemocraticNational Convention will be allocated among presidential candidatesin proportion to the results of the March 8 primary.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 45   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 8 and Friday, February 26   Tennessee Republicans will elect 33 of their national conventiondelegates directly from the primary ballot. The candidates fordelegate were to be arranged in slates on the ballot according topresidential preference.   The remaining 12 delegates from Tennessee will be chosen by thestate executive committee on March 26 and allocated amongpresidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary.</TEXT></DOC>